metadata.name: Traveling Circus #43
metadata.description:
A fun little project for the bear market.  Flow lines and shapes move between two flow fields.  Made in p5.js.  Finishes off using Dave Pagurek's grain shader.  For main shape color from palette, color #6 is sometimes best.  The code will mint exactly what you create with the parameters, while another minter will get a different result with the same parameters. 

Press "s" to save a 3500 x 3500 pixel png.

metadata.name: Why? #88
metadata.description:
The direction taken by the artwork Why? was taken when contemplating a canvas filled with what could be viewed as huge stone steps. I added the small stick people - were they climbing up or down? Where were they going? Where did they come from?
I then became interested in how subtle changes of background colour and changes of balloon colour changed the story, or the feeling of the story - ranging from bright hope to despair and futility. 

All p5.js.
The artwork is rendered at window size, use keys '2' and '3' to render larger.

metadata.name: Flow #56
metadata.description:
Flow is an ode to the boundless creativity and imaginative spirit that resides within each of us. 

The colour palettes for this piece are sampled from significant female and male abstract artists from throughout the last 600 years. Many of these palettes are generated by sampling colours from photos captured while visiting and viewing their pieces in person.

This is my second collection in my generative art journey. 

The code to create this collection can be found here: https://github.com/gitpancake/flow

Prepare to be entranced by "Lines of Illusion," a captivating series of generative artworks. Dive into a world of optical illusions, where meticulously crafted linear maps create mind-bending visual tricks, challenging your perception and leaving you in awe.
